{"id":5294,"date":"2022-09-25T04:23:00","date_gmt":"2022-09-25T04:23:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/?p=5294"},"modified":"2022-09-21T04:25:53","modified_gmt":"2022-09-21T04:25:53","slug":"experiencing-khun-yuam-where-to-go-what-to-do","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/experiencing-khun-yuam-where-to-go-what-to-do\/","title":{"rendered":"Experiencing Khun Yuam: Where to go, what to do&#8230;"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>Khun Yuam is a town in the Mae Hong Son Province. Northern Thailand is very different to other parts of Thailand and Khun Yuam is a great place to stop as you tour this region!<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>What To Eat&#8230;<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>There are many great places to get delicious Thai food and also coffee and snacks in Khun Yuam. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The 7-11 and Lotus Supermarkets are great places to get your groceries and also find delicious convenience store food and snacks. You will definitely want to try what they have and they are easily located on the main road in town. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Restaurants such as Khraw Mai Kao, Khraw Kra Tin and Sa La Win&nbsp;are also on the main road and serve fresh, authentic Thai food. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There are also many cafes that serve food and drinks including coffee with orange juice! Some of our favourites are: <\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>Parley Farm, where you can drink fresh coconut water and look out into the rice paddies. &nbsp;<\/li><li>Dad\u2019s Garden, which is open until late, has a lovely view and is a great place to relax. <\/li><li>Duang Yi War Cafe, has a lovely view and is a buffet\/barbeque spot at night. <\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.17.30-AM-768x1024.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-5322\" width=\"367\" height=\"489\" srcset=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.17.30-AM-768x1024.jpeg 768w, https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.17.30-AM-225x300.jpeg 225w, https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.17.30-AM.jpeg 900w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 367px) 100vw, 367px\" \/><figcaption>Thai Spaghetti and a view<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>Where To Stay..<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>If you need to stop for a night or want to stay longer, there are hotels in Khun Yuam such as the Yoont Hotel and Mit Khun Yuam Hotel in the main part of town. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There is also the Khun Yuam Resort which has beautiful views of the forest and it just out of town. This is a place to stay if you want a break from any hustle and bustle. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There are more rest houses and places to stay such as the Sununcha Resort and Ban Farang Resthouse which are reopening as Covid restrictions lessen. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>What To Do&#8230;<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>Bua Tong\/ Mexican Sunflower Fields: From November to December you can see these fields in bloom and enjoy a scenic day out. <\/li><li>Mae Yuam Luang Waterfall: A small but lovely waterfall you can see after a short hike through the forest. Watch out for the leeches in rainy season and wear socks! <\/li><li>Mae Sue Rin Waterfall: One of the tallest waterfalls in Thailand. <\/li><li>Sor Tue Lake: Full of standing dead trees, the lake is serene and a nice picnic or camping spot. <\/li><li>Thai-Japanese Friendship Memorial: A small museum with where you can learn about Khun Yuam&#8217;s history. <\/li><li>Do Moi Yar Temple: A walk uphill will show you this lovely temple and a great view of Khun Yuam district. <\/li><li>Tor Phae Temple: Considered the most beautiful temple in the area, it is worth a look!<\/li><li>Markets: There is a lovely little Saturday morning market in Khun Yuam where you can get fruit, veg and snacks. The fried papaya fritters are a must! <\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped\">\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"900\" height=\"1200\" data-id=\"5323\"  src=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.54-AM.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-5323\" srcset=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.54-AM.jpeg 900w, https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.54-AM-225x300.jpeg 225w, https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.54-AM-768x1024.jpeg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" \/><figcaption>Mae Surin Waterfall<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"827\" height=\"606\" data-id=\"5321\"  src=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.52-AM.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-5321\" srcset=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.52-AM.jpeg 827w, https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.52-AM-300x220.jpeg 300w, https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.52-AM-768x563.jpeg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 827px) 100vw, 827px\" \/><figcaption>The Mexican Sunflower Fields<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"900\" height=\"1200\" data-id=\"5320\"  src=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.07-AM.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-5320\" srcset=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.07-AM.jpeg 900w, https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.07-AM-225x300.jpeg 225w, https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/09\/WhatsApp-Image-2022-09-21-at-5.08.07-AM-768x1024.jpeg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" \/><figcaption>Street food in Khun Yuam<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Getting around Khun Yuam isn&#8217;t always easy, and many people use mopeds or bikes. You can get minivans or shared taxis to and from Mae Hong Son and there is a daily bus to Chiang Mai that leaves twice a day and also arrives twice a day from Chiang Mai. It is easy to walk around the town itself to places to eat and shop. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>KHT volunteers often live in Khun Yuam or the villages surrounding it and it is a unique experience that they remember for the rest of their lives. You can find out more about how to volunteer with KHT <a href=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/volunteer-in-thailand\/\">here<\/a>. <\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Khun Yuam is a town in the Mae&#8230;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":4,"featured_media":5319,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"_mi_skip_tracking":false},"categories":[1],"tags":[],"acf":[],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v19.12 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<title>Experiencing Khun Yuam: Where to go, what to do... - Karen Hilltribes Trust<\/title>\n<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow, max-snippet:-1, max-image-preview:large, max-video-preview:-1\" \/>\n<link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https:\/\/karenhilltribes.org.uk\/experiencing-khun-yuam-where-to-go-what-to-do\/\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:locale\" content=\"en_US\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"article\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Experiencing Khun Yuam: Where to go, what to do... - Karen Hilltribes Trust\